  "text": "Django's SQL injection prevention for raw SQL queries is implemented through a multi-layered architecture that separates SQL code from parameters at every stage of query execution.\n\n## RawSQL Expression Sanitization\n\nThe **RawSQL** class (django/db/models/expressions.py:1236-1249) is the primary mechanism for safely writing raw SQL expressions. It requires developers to pass SQL and parameters separately: `RawSQL(sql, params, output_field=None)`. The params argument is mandatory and cannot be omitted, forcing developers to acknowledge they are using parameterization.\n\n## Raw QuerySet Method Parameter Binding\n\nThe **QuerySet.raw()** method (django/db/models/query.py:1461-1473) accepts raw_query and params arguments separately. This method creates a RawQuerySet instance that passes both the SQL string and parameters through the execution pipeline without interpolating them together.\n\nThe **RawQuerySet** class (django/db/models/query.py:2285-2350) stores the raw SQL query and parameters separately, maintaining this separation throughout the object's lifetime.\n\n## Cursor.execute() Parameterization Enforcement\n\nThe critical execution point is in **RawQuery._execute_query()** (django/db/models/sql/query.py:208-225), which:\n\n1. Adapts parameters using `connection.ops.adapt_unknown_value()` to convert them to database-compatible types\n2. Passes the SQL and adapted parameters separately to `cursor.execute(sql, params)` - never interpolating them together\n3. Handles both tuple and dictionary parameter types (pyformat and named styles)\n\nThe **CursorWrapper** class (django/db/backends/utils.py:17-150) wraps all cursor execution through:\n\n- **execute()** method (lines 78-81): Routes to `_execute_with_wrappers()` with sql and params separated\n- **executemany()** method (lines 83-86): Routes to `_execute_with_wrappers()` for batch execution\n- **_execute()** method (lines 94-105): Calls underlying `cursor.execute(sql, params)` with separated parameters\n- **_execute_with_wrappers()** method (lines 88-92): Allows execution wrappers while maintaining parameter separation\n\n## Backend-Specific Parameter Handling\n\nEach database backend implements parameter binding protection:\n\n**SQLite** (django/db/backends/sqlite3/base.py:340-379):\n- **SQLiteCursorWrapper** converts Django's parameter styles (\"format\" and \"pyformat\") to SQLite's native styles (\"qmark\" and \"named\")\n- **execute()** and **executemany()** methods (lines 353-370) perform parameter style conversion while maintaining separation\n- **convert_query()** method (lines 372-378) safely transforms placeholders without interpolating parameters\n\n**PostgreSQL** (django/db/backends/postgresql/base.py:575-621):\n- **ServerBindingCursor** enables server-side parameter binding when using psycopg3\n- **Cursor** uses client-side parameter binding with psycopg3/psycopg2\n- **ServerSideCursor** for named cursor support with client-side binding enforcement\n\n**Oracle** (django/db/backends/oracle/base.py):\n- **OracleParam** class with **bind_parameter()** method handles late-binding cursor variables\n- Parameters are wrapped in cursor variables before execution\n\n## Parameter Type Adaptation\n\nThe **BaseDatabaseOperations.adapt_unknown_value()** method (django/db/backends/base/operations.py:550-567) transforms Python values to database-compatible types:\n\n- Converts datetime.datetime to adapted datetime values\n- Converts datetime.date to string representation\n- Converts datetime.time to adapted time values  \n- Converts decimal.Decimal to adapted decimal values\n- Maintains type safety to prevent type-coercion attacks\n\n## Execution Wrapper System\n\nThe **CursorDebugWrapper** (django/db/backends/utils.py:117-150) wraps cursor execution for debugging while maintaining parameter separation through the `debug_sql()` context manager.\n\nAll execution goes through `_execute_with_wrappers()` which applies execute_wrappers while keeping sql and params separated throughout the call chain.\n\n## Documentation\n\nSQL injection protection is documented in:\n- docs/topics/security.txt - SQL injection protection overview\n- docs/topics/db/sql.txt - Raw query and parameter binding guidance\n- docs/ref/models/expressions.txt - RawSQL expression requirements\n\nThe documentation emphasizes that params is a required argument and must not quote placeholders (e.g., avoid `RawSQL(\"WHERE col = '%s'\")` in favor of `RawSQL(\"WHERE col = %s\", [value])`)\n\n## Test Coverage\n\nSQL injection prevention is tested in tests/expressions/tests.py with `test_expressions_not_introduce_sql_injection_via_untrusted_string_inclusion()` demonstrating that malicious SQL injection attempts through expression filters are neutralized by parameter binding."
}

